        "body": "The chapter opens with a military frame that keeps David deliberately in view before removing him from the scene. Achish's demand that David serve as his bodyguard (28:1-2) and David's opaque response ('you shall know what your servant can do') are left unresolved — the narrator will pick up this thread in chapter 29. The effect is to establish the contrast that governs the whole section of 1 Samuel 27-31: David, who has God's favor, navigates impossible political situations with apparent safety; Saul, from whom God has departed, faces an ordinary military threat and immediately collapses.\n\nThe expository parenthesis of 28:3 is crucial. The narrator inserts two facts: Samuel is dead and buried in Ramah; Saul had removed mediums from the land. Both facts are already known to the reader (1 Samuel 25:1 for Samuel's death; the medium-ban is implied by Mosaic law and Saul's earlier general compliance). The narrator repeats them here because both are about to become ironic. The man who did the right thing about mediums is about to seek one; the prophet whose voice Saul needed is gone. The two facts together define the trap: the legitimate resource is dead; the illegitimate one has been suppressed by the very man who now needs it.\n\nVerse 5 gives the psychological portrait with precision: Saul *saw* the Philistine camp and his heart *trembled greatly*. The narrator does not say Saul assessed the situation, called a council, or prayed. He saw and trembled. This is not military prudence but existential terror — the kind of fear that strips a man of rational agency. It is from this terror that the inquiry of 28:6 arises. And the inquiry is real — Saul does turn to the LORD. The tragedy of 28:6 is not that Saul fails to try the right channel; it is that the channel has been closed by his own history. Three authorized means, all silent. The verb used for God's non-answering (*un*) is the same verb used elsewhere when God *does* answer (e.g., 1 Samuel 14:37, where God does not answer Saul — an earlier silence that prefigures this one).\n\nThe silence of 28:6 is the most important theological fact in the chapter. It is not passive — it is the active posture of a God who has already spoken His final word through Samuel at Ramah (1 Samuel 15:26-28) and will not repeat it through any of the three channels Saul consults. John Calvin comments on this passage that God's silence toward the impenitent is itself a form of judgment, not of indifference — He is not absent but refusing to speak to one who has not received what He already said.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Shaal* (to ask, inquire) at 28:6 is the root of Saul's own name — the narrator's pun is pointed: the man named 'asked for' (by the people, 1 Samuel 8:5) now asks of the LORD and receives nothing. *Un* (to answer) appears at both 28:6 and 28:15, forming a bracket around the consultation: God does not answer; Samuel asks Saul why he expects Samuel to do what God refuses to do."
