        "body": "The sequence of 28:7-10 maps the logic of spiritual desperation with clinical accuracy. God does not answer → seek a medium → disguise yourself → travel at night → swear by the God you have abandoned that the practitioner will not be punished. Each step is the direct consequence of the one before it, and each step takes Saul further from who he was.\n\nThe command to his servants ('seek for me a woman who is a medium,' 28:7) is the first formal breach. The Mosaic prohibitions are unambiguous: Leviticus 19:31 ('Do not turn to mediums or spiritists'), Leviticus 20:6 (the person who turns to mediums 'I will set my face against'), Deuteronomy 18:10-12 (consulting mediums is 'an abomination to the LORD'). Saul recites Mosaic law to the medium herself in 28:9 — he knows the law; he is choosing to violate it. This is not ignorance but deliberate transgression, the most serious kind in the biblical framework.\n\nThe disguise (*chaphas*, 28:8) is both practical and symbolic. Practically, Saul must avoid recognition — if anyone reports to the Philistines that Israel's king is consulting occult practitioners the night before battle, it is militarily catastrophic. But symbolically, the disguise is the outward form of a much deeper hiding: Saul has been hiding from who he is since at least 1 Samuel 15:30, when he asked Samuel to honor him before the elders even as Samuel was announcing his rejection. He has been performing the role of king while the substance of kingship — the divine favor — had been transferred. The other clothes he puts on in 28:8 are the final form of this performance.\n\nThe oath of 28:10 is the chapter's most grotesque moment. Saul swears *by the LORD* that no punishment will come upon the woman for a practice that the LORD has prohibited under penalty of death. He invokes the name of the God whose silence drove him here to authorize an act that silence was supposed to prevent. The covenant name — *yehovah* — appears twice in the oath: 'As the LORD lives...' This is not merely ironic; it is the formal desecration of the divine name in the service of idolatrous inquiry.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Chaphas* (disguised himself, 28:8) is used in military contexts for reconnaissance and concealment (e.g., 1 Kings 22:30, where Ahab disguises himself before the battle in which he is killed — a potentially significant parallel). *Ov* (medium, spirit, 28:3, 7, 8, 9) likely derives from a word for 'hollow vessel' or 'pit,' referring to a spirit that speaks from below — the direction of 28:13 ('coming up out of the earth') confirms this spatial orientation."
