        "body": "Samuel's speech is the theological center of the chapter and of Saul's entire story. It is composed of five movements, each of which closes a door: (1) reproach for the disturbance (28:15a); (2) refusal to function as substitute for God (28:16); (3) confirmation that the LORD's word through Samuel has now been executed (28:17); (4) naming the root cause (28:18); (5) announcement of the execution timetable (28:19).\n\nThe most devastating single statement is 28:16: 'the LORD has departed from you and has become your adversary.' The Hebrew word translated 'adversary' (*ar*, from *tsarar*, to bind tightly, to be hostile) has legal and military overtones — it is the posture of an opponent in a lawsuit or a battle. The God who anointed Saul, gave him the Spirit, and equipped him for kingship has moved to the other side. This is not abandonment in the sense of indifference; it is active opposition. Saul does not simply lack divine aid; he has divine resistance. Douglas Stuart and others in the Reformed tradition see this as the covenant curse language of Leviticus 26:17 ('I will set my face against you') arriving in narrative form.\n\nVerse 17 is the confirmation verse: 'The LORD has done accordingly as He spoke through me.' Samuel does not offer fresh revelation but authentication of old revelation. The word of 1 Samuel 15:28 ('the LORD has torn the kingdom of Israel from you today') is now in its past-tense form: it has been done. The present moment at En-dor is the formal arrival of a judgment that was already established. Reformed and Lutheran interpreters have consistently noted that this is how God's prophetic word works — it does not become true when it is fulfilled; it was always true and fulfillment simply makes that truth visible.\n\nThe naming of David in 28:17 ('given it to your neighbor, to David') is the first explicit identification of the recipient of the kingdom in a scene with Saul. David's name appears here not as comfort but as specification — the transfer is to a particular person, and Saul knows exactly who that person is. Samuel's use of 'neighbor' (*rea*) echoes 1 Samuel 15:28 verbatim, where the same word appeared ('a neighbor of yours who is better than you'), now filled in with the name.\n\nThe announcement of 28:19 — 'tomorrow you and your sons will be with me' — functions on two levels. On the narrative level, it predicts the battle's outcome, confirmed by chapter 31. On the theological level, 'with me' (with Samuel, in the realm of the dead) is one of the most discussed phrases in the chapter. It implies that both Samuel and Saul, and Saul's sons, share the same post-mortem destination — which has been taken variously to mean Sheol generally (the realm of the dead, without moral differentiation) or as suggestive of more (given Samuel's status). The text does not press the point; the narrator's interest is in the imminence and certainty of death, not in a detailed eschatology of the afterlife.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Tsarar* / *ar* (adversary, 28:16) — from a root meaning to bind, press, be hostile; appears in legal contexts (Isaiah 11:13) and military ones (Numbers 10:9). *Mamlakhah* (kingdom, 28:17) — the royal domain and authority; its being 'torn' (*qarah* in 15:27-28; the LXX uses *diaspar*, to tear apart) uses the same verb/image as the physical tearing of the robe at Gilgal. *Machar* (tomorrow, 28:19) — the most frequent Hebrew time-word, here carrying existential finality."
