        "body": "The chapter's final movement shifts abruptly from the supernatural register of 28:15-19 to the deeply physical register of 28:20-25, and the shift is itself part of the narrator's argument. The man who has just received a divine death sentence is lying full length on the ground, terrified, with no strength — his body has given out along with his spirit. The fasting detail (28:20) is significant: he has eaten nothing all day and all night, suggesting that the inquiry of 28:6 and the journey to En-dor were preceded by what may have been an attempted fast of petition, or simply the paralysis of a man who cannot eat while facing what he is facing.\n\nThe woman's response is quietly extraordinary. She has been paid nothing, threatened with death (28:9), protected only by a royal oath sworn in the name of a God Saul has evidently abandoned (28:10), and forced to conduct her most dangerous consultation for a king who lied about his identity. She now argues with the prostrate king, enlists his servants, slaughters her best animal, and bakes bread in the middle of the night. The narrator records her actions in five verbs (28:24): she slaughtered, took, kneaded, baked, and brought. This is not reluctant compliance; it is energetic care.\n\nCalvin, in his commentary on this passage, refuses to moralize the woman's kindness into a lesson about mediums and instead focuses on the providential dimension: even in Saul's absolute degradation, God provides bread sufficient to sustain the king until the judgment can be executed. The meal is not grace in the redemptive sense — it changes nothing about what tomorrow will bring — but it is what Augustine would call a mercy of preservation, the common grace that maintains life even where saving grace has been forfeited.\n\nThe final verse (28:25) is flat and devastatingly simple: 'They arose and went away that night.' There is no resolution, no hope, no prayer, no repentance recorded. Saul gets up, eats, and walks into the dark toward tomorrow. The chapter that began with military mobilization (28:1) ends with a silent departure into night. The narrator gives us no interior view of Saul's mind as he walks toward Gilboa. We only know that he goes — toward the battle Samuel has told him he will lose, toward the death Samuel has told him will come, toward the God who has become his adversary.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Matstsah* (unleavened bread, 28:24) — Passover bread, bread of haste and deliverance (Exodus 12:8, 15-20). The use here may be incidental or may carry ironic resonance: the unleavened bread of Israel's founding deliverance is baked by an Endorean medium for a condemned king. *Naphal* (fell, 28:20) — the same word used for falling in battle; Saul's collapse onto the ground anticipates his fall on Gilboa in 31:4. *Mahar* (quickly, 28:24) — the same word used of the woman in 28:20's immediate response; she wastes no time caring for what she has been ordered to serve."
